# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: imu-sensors
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] The direction ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\omega }}}={\boldsymbol {\omega }}/\|{\boldsymbol {\omega }}\|$ is normal to the instantaneous plane of rotation.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] The sense of angular velocity is conventionally specified by the right-hand rule, implying clockwise rotations (as viewed on the plane of rotation); negation (multiplication by −1) leaves the magnitude unchanged but flips the axis in the opposite direction.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] The magnitude of this vector, $\omega =\|{\boldsymbol {\omega }}\|$ , represents the *angular speed*, the angular rate at which the object rotates (spins or revolves).
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] The angular velocity as given above for point particles, is called orbital angular velocity.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] A rigid body rotating about a fixed axis has each point of the body having the same orbital angular velocity.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] Hence such a rigid body can be given an angular velocity (called spin angular velocity) equal to the orbital angular velocity of each point in the body.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] The angular velocity, as given above for rotation in a fixed circle at constant speed, can be generalized to more general motion in three dimensions.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] Angular velocity has dimension of per unit time.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] The SI unit of angular velocity is radians per second,.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] The radian is a dimensionless quantity, thus the SI units of angular velocity are dimensionally equivalent to reciprocal seconds, s−1, although rad/s is preferable to avoid confusion with **rotational velocity** in units of hertz (also equivalent to s−1).
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] If angle is measured in radians, the linear velocity is the radius times the angular velocity, ⁠ $v=r\omega$ ⁠.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] With orbital radius 42000 km from the Earth's center, the satellite's tangential speed through space is thus *v* = 42000 km × 0.26/h ≈ 11000 km/h.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] The angular velocity is positive since the satellite travels prograde with the Earth's rotation (the same direction as the rotation of Earth).
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] In the simplest case of circular motion at radius ⁠ r ⁠, with position given by the angular displacement $\phi (t)$ from the x-axis, the orbital angular velocity is the rate of change of angle with respect to time: ⁠ $\textstyle \omega ={\frac {d\phi }{dt}}$ ⁠.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] If $\phi$ is measured in radians, the arc-length from the positive x-axis around the circle to the particle is ⁠ $\ell =r\phi$ ⁠, and the linear velocity is ⁠ $\textstyle v(t)={\frac {d\ell }{dt}}=r\omega (t)$ ⁠, so that ⁠ $\textstyle \omega ={\frac {v}{r}}$ ⁠.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] In the general case of a particle moving in the plane, the orbital angular velocity is the rate at which the position vector relative to a chosen origin "sweeps out" angle.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] The diagram shows the position vector $\mathbf {r}$ from the origin O to a particle ⁠ P ⁠, with its polar coordinates ⁠ $(r,\phi )$ ⁠.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] When there is no radial component, the particle moves around the origin in a circle; but when there is no cross-radial component, it moves in a straight line from the origin.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] Since radial motion leaves the angle unchanged, only the cross-radial component of linear velocity contributes to angular velocity.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] Here the cross-radial speed $v_{\perp }$ is the signed magnitude of ⁠ $\mathbf {v} _{\perp }$ ⁠, positive for counter-clockwise motion, negative for clockwise.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] These formulas may be derived doing ⁠ $\mathbf {r} =(r\cos(\varphi ),r\sin(\varphi ))$ ⁠, being r a function of the distance to the origin with respect to time, and $\varphi$ a function of the angle between the vector and the x-axis.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] In two dimensions, angular velocity is a number with plus or minus sign indicating orientation, but not pointing in a direction.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] The sign is conventionally taken to be positive if the radius vector turns counter-clockwise, and negative if clockwise.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] Angular velocity then may be termed a pseudoscalar, a numerical quantity which changes sign under a parity inversion, such as inverting one axis or switching the two axes.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] In three-dimensional space, we again have the position vector **r** of a moving particle.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] Here, orbital angular velocity is a pseudovector whose magnitude is the rate at which **r** sweeps out angle (in radians per unit of time), and whose direction is perpendicular to the instantaneous plane in which **r** sweeps out angle (i.e. the plane spanned by **r** and **v**).
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] However, as there are *two* directions perpendicular to any plane, an additional condition is necessary to uniquely specify the direction of the angular velocity; conventionally, the right-hand rule is used.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] Let the pseudovector $\mathbf {u}$ be the unit vector perpendicular to the plane spanned by **r** and **v**, so that the right-hand rule is satisfied (i.e. the instantaneous direction of angular displacement is counter-clockwise looking from the top of ⁠ $\mathbf {u}$ ⁠).
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] where ⁠ $\theta$ ⁠ is the angle between ⁠ $\mathbf {r}$ ⁠ and ⁠ $\mathbf {v}$ ⁠.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] Given a rotating frame of three linearly independent unit coordinate vectors, at each instant in time, there always exists a common axis (called the axis of rotation) around which all three vectors rotate with the same angular speed and in the same angular direction (clockwise or counterclockwise).
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] In such a frame, each vector may be considered as a moving particle with constant scalar radius.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] A collection of such particles is called a rigid body.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] In larger than 3 spatial dimensions, the interpretation of spin angular velocity as a pseudovector is not valid; however, it may be characterized by a more general type of object known as an antisymmetric rank-2 tensor.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] The addition of angular velocity vectors for frames is also defined by the usual vector addition (composition of linear movements), and can be useful to decompose the rotation as in a gimbal.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] All components of the vector can be calculated as derivatives of the parameters defining the moving frames (Euler angles or rotation matrices).
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] Consider a rigid body rotating about a fixed point O.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] Construct a reference frame in the body consisting of an orthonormal set of vectors $\mathbf {e} _{1},\mathbf {e} _{2},\mathbf {e} _{3}$ fixed to the body and with their common origin at O.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] where ${\dot {\mathbf {e} }}_{i}={\frac {d\mathbf {e} _{i}}{dt}}$ is the time rate of change of the frame vector ⁠ $\mathbf {e} _{i},i=1,2,3$ ⁠, due to the rotation.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] as that formula defines angular velocity for a *single point* about O, while the formula in this section applies to a frame or rigid body.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] In the case of a rigid body a *single* ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}$ has to account for the motion of *all* particles in the body.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] Euler proved that the projections of the angular velocity pseudovector on each of these three axes is the derivative of its associated angle (which is equivalent to decomposing the instantaneous rotation into three instantaneous Euler rotations).
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] This basis is not orthonormal and it is difficult to use, but now the velocity vector can be changed to the fixed frame or to the moving frame with just a change of bases.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] where ${\hat {\mathbf {i} }},{\hat {\mathbf {j} }},{\hat {\mathbf {k} }}$ are unit vectors for the frame fixed in the moving body.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] This example has been made using the Z-X-Z convention for Euler angles.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] The scalar elements above correspond to the angular velocity vector components ${\boldsymbol {\omega }}=(\omega _{x},\omega _{y},\omega _{z})$ .
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] This is an *infinitesimal rotation matrix*.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] where ${\boldsymbol {r}}$ is a position vector.
[src:imu-sensors/angular-velocity] When multiplied by a time difference, it results in the *angular displacement tensor*.
[src:imu-sensors/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] An **attitude and heading reference system** (**AHRS**) consists of sensors on three axes that provide attitude information for aircraft, including roll, pitch, and yaw.
[src:imu-sensors/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] These are sometimes referred to as **MARG** (Magnetic, Angular Rate, and Gravity) sensors and consist of either solid-state or microelectromechanical systems (MEMS) gyroscopes, accelerometers and magnetometers.
[src:imu-sensors/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] They are designed to replace traditional mechanical gyroscopic flight instruments.
[src:imu-sensors/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] The main difference between an Inertial measurement unit (IMU) and an AHRS is the addition of an on-board processing system in an AHRS, which provides attitude and heading information.
[src:imu-sensors/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] This is in contrast to an IMU, which delivers sensor data to an additional device that computes attitude and heading.
[src:imu-sensors/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] With sensor fusion, drift from the gyroscopes integration is compensated for by reference vectors, namely gravity, and the Earth's magnetic field.
[src:imu-sensors/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] This results in a drift-free orientation, making an AHRS a more cost effective solution than conventional high-grade IMUs that only integrate gyroscopes and rely on a high bias stability of the gyroscopes.
[src:imu-sensors/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] In addition to attitude determination an AHRS may also form part of an inertial navigation system.
[src:imu-sensors/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] A form of non-linear estimation such as an Extended Kalman filter is typically used to compute the solution from these multiple sources.
[src:imu-sensors/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] AHRS is reliable and is common in commercial and business aircraft.
[src:imu-sensors/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] AHRS is typically integrated with electronic flight instrument systems (EFIS) which are the central part of glass cockpits, to form the primary flight display.
[src:imu-sensors/attitude-and-heading-reference-system] AHRS can be combined with air data computers to form an Air data, attitude and heading reference system (ADAHRS), which provide additional information such as airspeed, altitude and outside air temperature.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] In navigation, **dead reckoning** is the process of calculating the current position of a moving object by using a previously determined position, or fix, and incorporating estimates of speed, heading (or direction or course), and elapsed time.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] The corresponding term in biology, to describe the processes by which animals update their estimates of position or heading, is path integration.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Advances in navigational aids that give accurate information on position, in particular satellite navigation using the Global Positioning System, have made simple dead reckoning by humans obsolete for most purposes.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] However, inertial navigation systems, which provide very accurate directional information, use dead reckoning and are very widely applied.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Contrary to myth, the term "dead reckoning" was not originally used to abbreviate "deduced reckoning", nor is it a misspelling of the term "ded reckoning".
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] The use of "ded" or "deduced reckoning" is not known to have appeared earlier than 1931, much later in history than "dead reckoning", which appeared as early as 1613 according to the Oxford English Dictionary.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] The original intention of "dead" in the term is generally assumed to mean using a stationary object that is "dead in the water" as a basis for calculations.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Additionally, at the time the first appearance of "dead reckoning", "ded" was considered a common spelling of "dead".
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] This potentially led to later confusion of the origin of the term.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] By analogy with their navigational use, the words *dead reckoning* are also used to mean the process of estimating the value of any variable quantity by using an earlier value and adding whatever changes have occurred in the meantime.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Often, this usage implies that the changes are not known accurately.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] The earlier value and the changes may be measured or calculated quantities.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] While dead reckoning can give the best available information on the present position with little math or analysis, it is subject to significant errors of approximation.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] For precise positional information, both speed and direction must be accurately known at all times during travel.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Most notably, dead reckoning does not account for directional drift during travel through a fluid medium.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] These errors tend to compound themselves over greater distances, making dead reckoning a difficult method of navigation for longer journeys.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] For example, if displacement is measured by the number of rotations of a wheel, any discrepancy between the actual and assumed traveled distance per rotation, due perhaps to slippage or surface irregularities, will be a source of error.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] As each estimate of position is relative to the previous one, errors are cumulative, or compounding, over time.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] The accuracy of dead reckoning can be increased significantly by using other, more reliable methods to get a new fix part way through the journey.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] For example, if one was navigating on land in poor visibility, then dead reckoning could be used to get close enough to the known position of a landmark to be able to see it, before walking to the landmark itself—giving a precisely known starting point—and then setting off again.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Localizing a static sensor node is not a difficult task because attaching a Global Positioning System (GPS) device suffices the need of localization.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] But a mobile sensor node, which continuously changes its geographical location with time is difficult to localize.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Mostly mobile sensor nodes within some particular domain for data collection can be used, *i.e*, sensor node attached to an animal within a grazing field or attached to a soldier on a battlefield.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Within these scenarios a GPS device for each sensor node cannot be afforded.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Some of the reasons for this include cost, size and battery drainage of constrained sensor nodes.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] To overcome this problem a limited number of reference nodes (with GPS) within a field is employed.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] These nodes continuously broadcast their locations and other nodes in proximity receive these locations and calculate their position using some mathematical technique like trilateration.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] For localization, at least three known reference locations are necessary to localize.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Several localization algorithms based on Sequential Monte Carlo (SMC) method have been proposed in literature.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Sometimes a node at some places receives only two known locations and hence it becomes impossible to localize.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] To overcome this problem, dead reckoning technique is used.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] With this technique a sensor node uses its previous calculated location for localization at later time intervals.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] For example, at time instant 1 if node A calculates its position as *loca_1* with the help of three known reference locations; then at time instant 2 it uses *loca_1* along with two other reference locations received from other two reference nodes.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] This not only localizes a node in less time but also localizes in positions where it is difficult to get three reference locations.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] In studies of animal navigation, dead reckoning is more commonly (though not exclusively) known as path integration.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Animals use it to estimate their current location based on their movements from their last known location.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Animals such as ants, rodents, and geese have been shown to track their locations continuously relative to a starting point and to return to it, an important skill for foragers with a fixed home.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] In marine navigation a "dead" reckoning plot generally does not take into account the effect of currents or wind.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Aboard ship a dead reckoning plot is considered important in evaluating position information and planning the movement of the vessel.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Dead reckoning begins with a known position, or fix, which is then advanced, mathematically or directly on the chart, by means of recorded heading, speed, and time.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Speed can be determined by many methods.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Before modern instrumentation, it was determined aboard ship using a chip log.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] More modern methods include pit log referencing engine speed (*e.g*. in rpm) against a table of total displacement (for ships) or referencing one's indicated airspeed fed by the pressure from a pitot tube.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] This measurement is converted to an equivalent airspeed based upon known atmospheric conditions and measured errors in the indicated airspeed system.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] A naval vessel uses a device called a pit sword (rodmeter), which uses two sensors on a metal rod to measure the electromagnetic variance caused by the ship moving through water.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] This change is then converted to ship's speed.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Distance is determined by multiplying the speed and the time.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] This initial position can then be adjusted resulting in an estimated position by taking into account the current (known as set and drift in marine navigation).
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] If there is no positional information available, a new dead reckoning plot may start from an estimated position.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] In this case subsequent dead reckoning positions will have taken into account estimated set and drift.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Dead reckoning positions are calculated at predetermined intervals, and are maintained between fixes.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Factors including one's speed made good and the nature of heading and other course changes, and the navigator's judgment determine when dead reckoning positions are calculated.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Before the 18th-century development of the marine chronometer by John Harrison and the lunar distance method, dead reckoning was the primary method of determining longitude available to mariners such as Christopher Columbus and John Cabot on their trans-Atlantic voyages.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Tools such as the traverse board were developed to enable even illiterate crew members to collect the data needed for dead reckoning.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Polynesian navigation, however, uses different wayfinding techniques.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] On 14 June, 1919, John Alcock and Arthur Brown took off from Lester's Field in St.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] They navigated across the Atlantic Ocean by dead reckoning and landed in County Galway, Ireland at 8:40 a.m. on 15 June completing the first non-stop transatlantic flight.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] On 21 May 1927 Charles Lindbergh landed in Paris, France after a successful non-stop flight from the United States in the single-engined *Spirit of St.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] As the aircraft was equipped with very basic instruments, Lindbergh used dead reckoning to navigate.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Dead reckoning in the air is similar to dead reckoning on the sea, but slightly more complicated.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] The density of the air the aircraft moves through affects its performance as well as winds, weight, and power settings.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] The basic formula for DR is Distance = Speed x Time.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] An aircraft flying at 250 knots airspeed for 2 hours has flown 500 nautical miles through the air.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] The wind triangle is used to calculate the effects of wind on heading and airspeed to obtain a magnetic heading to steer and the speed over the ground (groundspeed).
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Printed tables, formulae, or an E6B flight computer are used to calculate the effects of air density on aircraft rate of climb, rate of fuel burn, and airspeed.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] A course line is drawn on the aeronautical chart along with estimated positions at fixed intervals (say every half hour).
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Visual observations of ground features are used to obtain fixes.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] By comparing the fix and the estimated position corrections are made to the aircraft's heading and groundspeed.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Dead reckoning is on the curriculum for VFR (visual flight rules – or basic level) pilots worldwide.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] It is taught regardless of whether the aircraft has navigation aids such as GPS, ADF and VOR and is an ICAO Requirement.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Many flying training schools will prevent a student from using electronic aids until they have mastered dead reckoning.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Inertial navigation systems (INSes), which are nearly universal on more advanced aircraft, use dead reckoning internally.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] The INS provides reliable navigation capability under virtually any conditions, without the need for external navigation references, although it is still prone to slight errors.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] The first automotive navigation systems pre-dated the availability of GPS and relied instead on dead reckoning-based systems.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Honda's Electro Gyrocator, launched in 1981, was the first commercially available car navigation system.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] It used inertial navigation systems, which tracked the distance traveled, the start point, and direction headed.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Dead reckoning is today implemented in some high-end automotive navigation systems in order to overcome the limitations of GPS/GNSS technology alone.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Satellite microwave signals are unavailable in parking garages and tunnels, and often severely degraded in urban canyons and near trees due to blocked lines of sight to the satellites or multipath propagation.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] In a dead-reckoning navigation system, the car is equipped with sensors that know the wheel circumference and record wheel rotations and steering direction.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] These sensors are often already present in cars for other purposes (anti-lock braking system, electronic stability control) and can be read by the navigation system from the controller-area network bus.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] The navigation system then uses a Kalman filter to integrate the always-available sensor data with the accurate but occasionally unavailable position information from the satellite data into a combined position fix.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Dead reckoning is utilized in some robotic applications.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] It is usually used to reduce the need for sensing technology, such as ultrasonic sensors, GPS, or placement of some linear and rotary encoders, in an autonomous robot, thus greatly reducing cost and complexity at the expense of performance and repeatability.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] The proper utilization of dead reckoning in this sense would be to supply a known percentage of electrical power or hydraulic pressure to the robot's drive motors over a given amount of time from a general starting point.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Dead reckoning is not totally accurate, which can lead to errors in distance estimates ranging from a few millimeters (in CNC machining) to kilometers (in UAVs), based upon the duration of the run, the speed of the robot, the length of the run, and several other factors.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] With the increased sensor offering in smartphones, built-in accelerometers can be used as a pedometer and built-in magnetometer as a compass heading provider.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] **Pedestrian dead reckoning** (**PDR**) can be used to supplement other navigation methods in a similar way to automotive navigation, or to extend navigation into areas where other navigation systems are unavailable.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] In a simple implementation, the user holds their phone in front of them, and each step causes their position to move forward a fixed distance in the direction measured by the compass.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Accuracy is limited by the sensor precision, magnetic disturbances inside structures, and unknown variables such as carrying position and stride length.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Another challenge is differentiating walking from running, and recognizing movements like bicycling, climbing stairs, or riding an elevator.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Before phone-based systems existed, many custom PDR systems existed.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] While a pedometer can only be used to measure linear distance traveled, PDR systems have an embedded magnetometer for heading measurement.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Custom PDR systems can take many forms including special boots, belts, and watches, where the variability of carrying position has been minimized to better utilize magnetometer heading.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] True dead reckoning is fairly complicated, as it is not only important to minimize basic drift, but also to handle different carrying scenarios and movements, as well as hardware differences across phone models.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] The south-pointing chariot was an ancient Chinese device consisting of a two-wheeled horse-drawn vehicle which carried a pointer that was intended always to aim to the south, no matter how the chariot turned.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] The chariot pre-dated the navigational use of the magnetic compass, and could not *detect* the direction that was south.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Instead it used a kind of **directional dead reckoning**: at the start of a journey, the pointer was aimed southward by hand, using local knowledge or astronomical observations e.g. of the Pole Star.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Errors, as always with dead reckoning, would accumulate as distance traveled increased.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Networked games and simulation tools routinely use dead reckoning to predict where an actor should be right now, using its last known kinematic state (position, velocity, acceleration, orientation, and angular velocity).
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] This is primarily needed because it is impractical to send network updates at the rate that most games run, 60 Hz.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] This formula is used to move the object until a new update is received over the network.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] At that point, the problem is that there are now two kinematic states: the currently estimated position and the just received, actual position.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Resolving these two states in a believable way can be quite complex.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] One approach is to create a curve (e.g. cubic Bézier splines, centripetal Catmull–Rom splines, and Hermite curves) between the two states while still projecting into the future.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Another technique is to use projective velocity blending, which is the blending of two projections (last known and current) where the current projection uses a blending between the last known and current velocity over a set time.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] The first equation calculates a blended velocity $V_{b}$ given the client-side velocity at the time of the last server update $V_{0}$ and the last known server-side velocity ${\acute {V}}_{0}$ .
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] This essentially blends from the client-side velocity towards the server-side velocity for a smooth transition.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Note that ${\hat {T}}$ should go from zero (at the time of the server update) to one (at the time at which the next update should be arriving).
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] A late server update is unproblematic as long as ${\hat {T}}$ remains at one.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Next, two positions are calculated: firstly, the blended velocity $V_{b}$ and the last known server-side acceleration ${\acute {A}}_{0}$ are used to calculate $P_{t}$ .
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] This is a position which is projected from the client-side start position $P_{0}$ based on $T_{t}$ , the time which has passed since the last server update.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Secondly, the same equation is used with the last known server-side parameters to calculate the position projected from the last known server-side position ${\acute {P}}_{0}$ and velocity ${\acute {V}}_{0}$ , resulting in ${\acute {P}}_{t}$ .
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] Finally, the new position to display on the client $Pos$ is the result of interpolating from the projected position based on client information $P_{t}$ towards the projected position based on the last known server information ${\acute {P}}_{t}$ .
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] The resulting movement smoothly resolves the discrepancy between client-side and server-side information, even if this server-side information arrives infrequently or inconsistently.
[src:imu-sensors/dead-reckoning] It is also free of oscillations which spline-based interpolation may suffer from.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] An **inertial measurement unit** (**IMU**) is an electronic device that measures and reports a body's specific force, angular rate, and sometimes the orientation of the body, using a combination of accelerometers, gyroscopes, and sometimes magnetometers.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] When the magnetometer is included, IMUs are referred to as IMMUs.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] IMUs are typically used to maneuver modern vehicles including motorcycles, missiles, aircraft (an attitude and heading reference system), including uncrewed aerial vehicles (UAVs), among many others, and spacecraft, including satellites and landers.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] Recent developments allow for the production of IMU-enabled GPS devices; an IMU allows a GPS receiver to work when GPS-signals are unavailable, such as in tunnels, inside buildings, or when electronic interference is present.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] IMUs are used in VR headsets and smartphones, and also in motion tracked game controllers like the Wii Remote, Steam Controller, Nintendo Switch Pro Controller and the Dualsense.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] An inertial measurement unit works by detecting linear acceleration using one or more accelerometers and rotational rate using one or more gyroscopes.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] Some also include a magnetometer which is commonly used as a heading reference.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] Some IMUs, like the BNO055 used within Adafruit's 9-DOF IMU Breakout, include additional sensors like temperature.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] Typical configurations contain one accelerometer, gyro, and magnetometer per axis for each of the three principal axes: pitch, roll and yaw.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] IMUs are often incorporated into Inertial Navigation Systems, which utilize the raw IMU measurements to calculate attitude, angular rates, linear velocity, and position relative to a global reference frame.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] The IMU equipped INS forms the backbone for the navigation and control of many commercial and military vehicles, such as crewed aircraft, missiles, ships, submarines, and satellites.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] IMUs are also essential components in the guidance and control of uncrewed systems such as UAVs, UGVs, and UUVs.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] Simpler versions of INSs termed Attitude and Heading Reference Systems utilize IMUs to calculate vehicle attitude with heading relative to magnetic north.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] The data collected from the IMU's sensors allows a computer to track craft's position, using a method known as dead reckoning.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] This data is usually presented in Euler vectors representing the angles of rotation in the three primary axis or a quaternion.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] Besides navigational purposes, IMUs serve as orientation sensors in many consumer products.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] Almost all smartphones and tablets contain IMUs as orientation sensors.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] Fitness trackers and other wearables may also include IMUs to measure motion, such as running.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] IMUs also have the ability to determine developmental levels of individuals when in motion by identifying specificity and sensitivity of specific parameters associated with running.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] Some gaming systems such as the remote controls for the Nintendo Wii use IMUs to measure motion.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] Low-cost IMUs have enabled the proliferation of the consumer drone industry.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] They are also frequently used for sports technology (technique training), and animation applications.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] They are a competing technology for use in motion capture technology.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] An IMU is at the heart of the balancing technology used in the Segway Personal Transporter.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] In a navigation system, the data reported by the IMU is fed into a processor which calculates altitude, velocity and position.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] A typical implementation referred to as a Strap Down Inertial System integrates angular rate from the gyroscope to calculate angular position.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] This is fused with the gravity vector measured by the accelerometers in a Kalman filter to estimate attitude.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] The attitude estimate is used to transform acceleration measurements into an inertial reference frame (hence the term inertial navigation) where they are integrated once to get linear velocity, and twice to get linear position.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] This method of navigation is called dead reckoning.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] One of the earliest units was designed and built by Ford Instrument Company for the USAF to help aircraft navigate in flight without any input from outside the aircraft.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] Called the **Ground-Position Indicator**, once the pilot entered in the aircraft longitude and latitude at takeoff, the unit would show the pilot the longitude and latitude of the aircraft in relation to the ground.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] Positional tracking systems like GPS can be used to continually correct drift errors (an application of the Kalman filter).
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] A major disadvantage of using IMUs for navigation is that they typically suffer from accumulated error.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] Because the guidance system is continually integrating acceleration with respect to time to calculate velocity and position *(see dead reckoning)*, any measurement errors, however small, are accumulated over time.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] This leads to 'drift': an ever-increasing difference between where the system thinks it is located and the actual location.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] Due to integration a constant error in acceleration results in a linear error growth in velocity and a quadratic error growth in position.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] A constant error in attitude rate (gyro) results in a quadratic error growth in velocity and a cubic error growth in position.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] To get a rough idea, this means that, for a single, uncorrected accelerometer, the cheapest (at 100 mg) loses its ability to give 50-meter accuracy after around 10 seconds, while the best accelerometer (at 10 μg) loses its 50-meter accuracy after around 17 minutes.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] The accuracy of the inertial sensors inside a modern inertial measurement unit (IMU) has a more complex impact on the performance of an inertial navigation system (INS).
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] All these errors depend on various physical phenomena specific to each sensor technology.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] Depending on the targeted applications and to be able to make the proper sensor choice, it is very important to consider the needs regarding stability, repeatability, and environment sensitivity (mainly thermal and mechanical environments), on both short and long terms.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] Targeted performance for applications is, most of the time, better than a sensor's absolute performance.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] However, sensor performance is repeatable over time, with more or less accuracy, and therefore can be assessed and compensated to enhance its performance.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] This real-time performance enhancement is based on both sensors and IMU models.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] Complexity for these models will then be chosen according to the needed performance and the type of application considered.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] Ability to define this model is part of sensors and IMU manufacturers know-how.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] Sensors and IMU models are computed in factories through a dedicated calibration sequence using multi-axis turntables and climatic chambers.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] They can either be computed for each individual product or generic for the whole production.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] Calibration will typically improve a sensor's raw performance by at least two decades.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] High performance IMUs, or IMUs designed to operate under harsh conditions, are very often suspended by shock absorbers.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] Suspended IMUs can offer very high performance, even when submitted to harsh environments.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] Decreasing these errors tends to push IMU designers to increase processing frequencies, which becomes easier using recent digital technologies.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] However, developing algorithms able to cancel these errors requires deep inertial knowledge and strong intimacy with sensors/IMU design.
[src:imu-sensors/inertial-measurement-unit] On the other hand, if suspension is likely to enable IMU performance increase, it has a side effect on size and mass.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Because of the large surface area to volume ratio of MEMS, forces produced by ambient electromagnetism (e.g., electrostatic charges and magnetic moments), and fluid dynamics (e.g., surface tension and viscosity) are more important design considerations than with larger scale mechanical devices.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] MEMS technology is distinguished from molecular nanotechnology or molecular electronics in that the latter two must also consider surface chemistry.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The potential of very small machines was appreciated before the technology existed that could make them (see, for example, Richard Feynman's famous 1959 lecture "There's Plenty of Room at the Bottom").
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] MEMS became practical once they could be fabricated using modified semiconductor device fabrication technologies, normally used to make electronics.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] These include molding and plating, wet etching (KOH, TMAH) and dry etching (RIE and DRIE), electrical discharge machining (EDM), and other technologies capable of manufacturing small devices.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] They merge at the nanoscale into nanoelectromechanical systems (NEMS) and nanotechnology.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] An early example of a MEMS device is the resonant-gate transistor, an adaptation of the MOSFET, developed by Robert A.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Another early example is the resonistor, an electromechanical monolithic resonator patented by Raymond J.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] During the 1970s to early 1980s, a number of MOSFET microsensors were developed for measuring physical, chemical, biological and environmental parameters.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Wood (Co-PI) introduced the term "MEMS" by way of a proposal to DARPA (15 July 1986), titled "Micro Electro-Mechanical Systems (MEMS)", granted to the University of Utah.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The term "MEMS" was presented by way of an invited talk by S.C.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Jacobsen, titled "Micro Electro-Mechanical Systems (MEMS)", at the IEEE Micro Robots and Teleoperators Workshop, Hyannis, MA Nov.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The term "MEMS" was published by way of a submitted paper by J.E.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Grace, titled "SCOFSS: A Small Cantilevered Optical Fiber Servo System", in the IEEE Proceedings Micro Robots and Teleoperators Workshop, Hyannis, MA Nov.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] CMOS transistors have been manufactured on top of MEMS structures.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] There are two basic types of MEMS switch technology: capacitive and ohmic.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] A capacitive MEMS switch is developed using a moving plate or sensing element, which changes the capacitance.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Ohmic switches are controlled by electrostatically controlled cantilevers.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Ohmic MEMS switches can fail from metal fatigue of the MEMS actuator (cantilever) and contact wear, since cantilevers can deform over time.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The fabrication of MEMS evolved from the process technology in semiconductor device fabrication, i.e. the basic techniques are deposition of material layers, patterning by photolithography and etching to produce the required shapes.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] , ready availability of inexpensive high-quality materials, and ability to incorporate electronic functionality make silicon attractive for a wide variety of MEMS applications.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Silicon also has significant advantages engendered through its material properties.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] based on silicon are gaining increasing importance in the field of microelectronics and MEMS in particular.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] provides an economy of scale for the silicon industry, crystalline silicon is still a complex and relatively expensive material to produce.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Polymers on the other hand can be produced in huge volumes, with a great variety of material characteristics.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] applications such as disposable blood testing cartridges.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Metals can also be used to create MEMS elements.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] While metals do not have some of the advantages displayed by silicon in terms of mechanical properties, when used within their limitations, metals can exhibit very high degrees of reliability.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Metals can be deposited by electroplating, evaporation, and sputtering processes.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Commonly used metals include gold, nickel, aluminium, copper, chromium, titanium, tungsten, platinum, and silver.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] are increasingly applied in MEMS fabrication due to advantageous combinations of material properties.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] properties enabling sensors, for instance, with sensitivity to normal and shear forces.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] , making it possible to implement electrostatic MEMS actuation schemes with ultrathin beams.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Moreover, the high resistance of TiN against biocorrosion qualifies the material for applications in biogenic environments.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] with a 50 nm thin bendable TiN beam above a TiN ground plate.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Both can be driven as opposite electrodes of a capacitor, since the beam is fixed in electrically isolating side walls.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] When a fluid is suspended in the cavity its viscosity may be derived from bending the beam by electrical attraction to the ground plate and measuring the bending velocity.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] One of the basic building blocks in MEMS processing is the ability to deposit thin films of material with a thickness anywhere from one micrometre to about 100 micrometres.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The NEMS process is the same, although the measurement of film deposition ranges from a few nanometres to one micrometre.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] There are two types of deposition processes, as follows.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Physical vapor deposition ("PVD") consists of a process in which a material is removed from a target, and deposited on a surface.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Chemical deposition techniques include chemical vapor deposition (CVD), in which a stream of source gas reacts on the substrate to grow the material desired.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] This can be further divided into categories depending on the details of the technique, for example LPCVD (low-pressure chemical vapor deposition) and PECVD (plasma-enhanced chemical vapor deposition).
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Oxide films can also be grown by the technique of thermal oxidation, in which the (typically silicon) wafer is exposed to oxygen and/or steam, to grow a thin surface layer of silicon dioxide.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Patterning is the transfer of a pattern into a material.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Lithography in a MEMS context is typically the transfer of a pattern into a photosensitive material by selective exposure to a radiation source such as light.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] A photosensitive material is a material that experiences a change in its physical properties when exposed to a radiation source.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] If a photosensitive material is selectively exposed to radiation (e.g. by masking some of the radiation) the pattern of the radiation on the material is transferred to the material exposed, as the properties of the exposed and unexposed regions differs.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] This exposed region can then be removed or treated providing a mask for the underlying substrate.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Photolithography is typically used with metal or other thin film deposition, wet and dry etching.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Sometimes, photolithography is used to create structure without any kind of post etching.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] One example is SU8 based lens where SU8 based square blocks are generated.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Then the photoresist is melted to form a semi-sphere which acts as a lens.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The purpose, as with photolithography, is to create very small structures in the resist that can subsequently be transferred to the substrate material, often by etching.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] It was developed for manufacturing integrated circuits, and is also used for creating nanotechnology architectures.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The primary advantage of electron beam lithography is that it is one of the ways to beat the diffraction limit of light and make features in the nanometer range.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] This form of maskless lithography has found wide usage in photomask-making used in photolithography, low-volume production of semiconductor components, and research & development.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The key limitation of electron beam lithography is throughput, i.e., the very long time it takes to expose an entire silicon wafer or glass substrate.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] A long exposure time leaves the user vulnerable to beam drift or instability which may occur during the exposure.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Also, the turn-around time for reworking or re-design is lengthened unnecessarily if the pattern is not being changed the second time.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] It is known that focused-ion beam lithography has the capability of writing extremely fine lines (less than 50 nm line and space has been achieved) without proximity effect.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] However, because the writing field in ion-beam lithography is quite small, large area patterns must be created by stitching together the small fields.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Ion track technology is a deep cutting tool with a resolution limit around 8 nm applicable to radiation resistant minerals, glasses and polymers.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] It is capable of generating holes in thin films without any development process.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Structural depth can be defined either by ion range or by material thickness.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Aspect ratios up to several 104 can be reached.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The technique can shape and texture materials at a defined inclination angle.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Random pattern, single-ion track structures and an aimed pattern consisting of individual single tracks can be generated.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] X-ray lithography is a process used in the electronic industry to selectively remove parts of a thin film.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] It uses X-rays to transfer a geometric pattern from a mask to a light-sensitive chemical photoresist, or simply "resist", on the substrate.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] A series of chemical treatments then engraves the produced pattern into the material underneath the photoresist.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Diamond patterning is a method of forming diamond MEMS.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] It is achieved by the lithographic application of diamond films to a substrate such as silicon.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The patterns can be formed by selective deposition through a silicon dioxide mask, or by deposition followed by micromachining or focused ion beam milling.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] There are two basic categories of etching processes: wet etching and dry etching.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] In the former, the material is dissolved when immersed in a chemical solution.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] In the latter, the material is sputtered or dissolved using reactive ions or a vapor phase etchant.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Wet chemical etching consists of the selective removal of material by dipping a substrate into a solution that dissolves it.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The chemical nature of this etching process provides good selectivity, which means the etching rate of the target material is considerably higher than the mask material if selected carefully.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Wet etching can be performed using either isotropic wet etchants or anisotropic wet etchants.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Isotropic wet etchant etch in all directions of the crystalline silicon at approximately equal rates.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Anisotropic wet etchants preferably etch along certain crystal planes at faster rates than other planes, thereby allowing more complicated 3-D microstructures to be implemented.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Wet anisotropic etchants are often used in conjunction with boron etch stops wherein the surface of the silicon is heavily doped with boron resulting in a silicon material layer that is resistant to the wet etchants.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] This has been used in MEWS pressure sensor manufacturing for example.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Etching progresses at the same speed in all directions.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Long and narrow holes in a mask will produce v-shaped grooves in the silicon.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The surface of these grooves can be atomically smooth if the etch is carried out correctly, with dimensions and angles being extremely accurate.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Some single crystal materials, such as silicon, will have different etching rates depending on the crystallographic orientation of the substrate.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] This is known as anisotropic etching and one of the most common examples is the etching of silicon in KOH (potassium hydroxide), where Si <111> planes etch approximately 100 times slower than other planes (crystallographic orientations).
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Therefore, etching a rectangular hole in a (100)-Si wafer results in a pyramid shaped etch pit with 54.7° walls, instead of a hole with curved sidewalls as with isotropic etching.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Hydrofluoric acid is commonly used as an aqueous etchant for silicon dioxide (SiO 2, also known as BOX for SOI), usually in 49% concentrated form, 5:1, 10:1 or 20:1 BOE (buffered oxide etchant) or BHF (Buffered HF).
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] They were first used in medieval times for glass etching.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] It was used in IC fabrication for patterning the gate oxide until the process step was replaced by RIE.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Hydrofluoric acid is considered one of the more dangerous acids in the cleanroom.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Electrochemical etching (ECE) for dopant-selective removal of silicon is a common method to automate and to selectively control etching.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] An active p–n diode junction is required, and either type of dopant can be the etch-resistant ("etch-stop") material.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Boron is the most common etch-stop dopant.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] In combination with wet anisotropic etching as described above, ECE has been used successfully for controlling silicon diaphragm thickness in commercial piezoresistive silicon pressure sensors.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Selectively doped regions can be created either by implantation, diffusion, or epitaxial deposition of silicon.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Xenon difluoride (XeF 2) is a dry vapor phase isotropic etch for silicon originally applied for MEMS in 1995 at University of California, Los Angeles.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Primarily used for releasing metal and dielectric structures by undercutting silicon, XeF 2 has the advantage of a stiction-free release unlike wet etchants.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Its etch selectivity to silicon is very high, allowing it to work with photoresist, SiO 2, silicon nitride, and various metals for masking.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Its reaction to silicon is "plasmaless", is purely chemical and spontaneous and is often operated in pulsed mode.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Models of the etching action are available, and university laboratories and various commercial tools offer solutions using this approach.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Modern VLSI processes avoid wet etching, and use plasma etching instead.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Plasma etchers can operate in several modes by adjusting the parameters of the plasma.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Ordinary plasma etching operates between 0.1 and 5 Torr.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] (This unit of pressure, commonly used in vacuum engineering, equals approximately 133.3 pascals.) The plasma produces energetic free radicals, neutrally charged, that react at the surface of the wafer.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Since neutral particles attack the wafer from all angles, this process is isotropic.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Plasma etching can be isotropic, i.e., exhibiting a lateral undercut rate on a patterned surface approximately the same as its downward etch rate, or can be anisotropic, i.e., exhibiting a smaller lateral undercut rate than its downward etch rate.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Such anisotropy is maximized in deep reactive ion etching.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The use of the term anisotropy for plasma etching should not be conflated with the use of the same term when referring to orientation-dependent etching.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The source gas for the plasma usually contains small molecules rich in chlorine or fluorine.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] For instance, carbon tetrachloride (CCl4) etches silicon and aluminium, and trifluoromethane etches silicon dioxide and silicon nitride.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] A plasma containing oxygen is used to oxidize ("ash") photoresist and facilitate its removal.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Ion milling, or sputter etching, uses lower pressures, often as low as 10−4 Torr (10 mPa).
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] It bombards the wafer with energetic ions of noble gases, often Ar+, which knock atoms from the substrate by transferring momentum.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Because the etching is performed by ions, which approach the wafer approximately from one direction, this process is highly anisotropic.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] On the other hand, it tends to display poor selectivity.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Reactive-ion etching (RIE) operates under conditions intermediate between sputter and plasma etching (between 10−3 and 10−1 Torr).
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Deep reactive-ion etching (DRIE) modifies the RIE technique to produce deep, narrow features.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] In reactive-ion etching (RIE), the substrate is placed inside a reactor, and several gases are introduced.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] A plasma is struck in the gas mixture using an RF power source, which breaks the gas molecules into ions.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The ions accelerate towards, and react with, the surface of the material being etched, forming another gaseous material.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] This is known as the chemical part of reactive ion etching.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] There is also a physical part, which is similar to the sputtering deposition process.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] If the ions have high enough energy, they can knock atoms out of the material to be etched without a chemical reaction.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] It is a very complex task to develop dry etch processes that balance chemical and physical etching, since there are many parameters to adjust.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] By changing the balance it is possible to influence the anisotropy of the etching, since the chemical part is isotropic and the physical part highly anisotropic the combination can form sidewalls that have shapes from rounded to vertical.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Deep reactive ion etching (DRIE) is a special subclass of RIE that is growing in popularity.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] In this process, etch depths of hundreds of micrometers are achieved with almost vertical sidewalls.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The primary technology is based on the so-called "Bosch process", named after the German company Robert Bosch, which filed the original patent, where two different gas compositions alternate in the reactor.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Currently, there are two variations of the DRIE.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The first variation consists of three distinct steps (the original Bosch process) while the second variation only consists of two steps.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] In the 2nd variation, steps (i) and (iii) are combined.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The C 4F 8 creates a polymer on the surface of the substrate, and the second gas composition (SF 6 and O 2) etches the substrate.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The polymer is immediately sputtered away by the physical part of the etching, but only on the horizontal surfaces and not the sidewalls.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Since the polymer only dissolves very slowly in the chemical part of the etching, it builds up on the sidewalls and protects them from etching.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] As a result, etching aspect ratios of 50 to 1 can be achieved.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The process can easily be used to etch completely through a silicon substrate, and etch rates are 3–6 times higher than wet etching.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] After preparing a large number of MEMS devices on a silicon wafer, individual dies have to be separated, which is called die preparation in semiconductor technology.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] For some applications, the separation is preceded by wafer backgrinding in order to reduce the wafer thickness.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Wafer dicing may then be performed either by sawing using a cooling liquid or a dry laser process called stealth dicing.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Bulk micromachining is the oldest paradigm of silicon-based MEMS.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The whole thickness of a silicon wafer is used for building the micro-mechanical structures.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Silicon is machined using various etching processes.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Bulk micromachining has been essential in enabling high performance pressure sensors and accelerometers that changed the sensor industry in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Surface micromachining uses layers deposited on the surface of a substrate as the structural materials, rather than using the substrate itself.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Surface micromachining was created in the late 1980s to render micromachining of silicon more compatible with planar integrated circuit technology, with the goal of combining MEMS and integrated circuits on the same silicon wafer.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The original surface micromachining concept was based on thin polycrystalline silicon layers patterned as movable mechanical structures and released by sacrificial etching of the underlying oxide layer.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Interdigital comb electrodes were used to produce in-plane forces and to detect in-plane movement capacitively.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] This MEMS paradigm has enabled the manufacturing of low cost accelerometers for e.g. automotive air-bag systems and other applications where low performance and/or high g-ranges are sufficient.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Analog Devices has pioneered the industrialization of surface micromachining and has realized the co-integration of MEMS and integrated circuits.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Wafer bonding involves joining two or more substrates (usually having the same diameter) to one another to form a composite structure.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Each of these methods have specific uses depending on the circumstances.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Most wafer bonding processes rely on three basic criteria for successfully bonding: the wafers to be bonded are sufficiently flat; the wafer surfaces are sufficiently smooth; and the wafer surfaces are sufficiently clean.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The most stringent criteria for wafer bonding is usually the direct fusion wafer bonding since even one or more small particulates can render the bonding unsuccessful.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] In comparison, wafer bonding methods that use intermediary layers are often far more forgiving.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Both bulk and surface silicon micromachining are used in the industrial production of sensors, ink-jet nozzles, and other devices.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] But in many cases the distinction between these two has diminished.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] A new etching technology, deep reactive-ion etching, has made it possible to combine good performance typical of bulk micromachining with comb structures and in-plane operation typical of surface micromachining.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] While it is common in surface micromachining to have structural layer thickness in the range of 2 μm, in HAR silicon micromachining the thickness can be from 10 to 100 μm.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The materials commonly used in HAR silicon micromachining are thick polycrystalline silicon, known as epi-poly, and bonded silicon-on-insulator (SOI) wafers although processes for bulk silicon wafer also have been created (SCREAM).
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Bonding a second wafer by glass frit bonding, anodic bonding or alloy bonding is used to protect the MEMS structures.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Integrated circuits are typically not combined with HAR silicon micromachining.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Companies with strong MEMS programs come in many sizes.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Larger firms specialize in manufacturing high volume inexpensive components or packaged solutions for end markets such as automobiles, biomedical, and electronics.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Smaller firms provide value in innovative solutions and absorb the expense of custom fabrication with high sales margins.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Both large and small companies typically invest in R&D to explore new MEMS technology.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] The market for materials and equipment used to manufacture MEMS devices topped $1 billion worldwide in 2006.
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] Materials demand is driven by substrates, making up over 70 percent of the market, packaging coatings and increasing use of chemical mechanical planarization (CMP).
[src:imu-sensors/microelectromechanical-systems] While MEMS manufacturing continues to be dominated by used semiconductor equipment, there is a migration to 200mm lines and select new tools, including etch and bonding for certain MEMS applications.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] In astronomy, **precession** refers to any of several slow changes in an astronomical body's rotational or orbital parameters.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] An important example is the steady change in the orientation of the axis of rotation of the Earth, known as the precession of the equinoxes.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Torque-free precession implies that no external moment (torque) is applied to the body.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] In torque-free precession, the angular momentum is a constant, but the angular velocity vector changes orientation with time.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] What makes this possible is a time-varying moment of inertia, or more precisely, a time-varying inertia matrix.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] The inertia matrix is composed of the moments of inertia of a body calculated with respect to separate coordinate axes (e.g.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] If an object is asymmetric about its principal axis of rotation, the moment of inertia with respect to each coordinate direction will change with time, while preserving angular momentum.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] The result is that the component of the angular velocities of the body about each axis will vary inversely with each axis' moment of inertia.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] When an object is not perfectly rigid, inelastic dissipation will tend to damp torque-free precession, and the rotation axis will align itself with one of the inertia axes of the body.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] For a generic solid object without any axis of symmetry, the evolution of the object's orientation, represented (for example) by a rotation matrix **R** that transforms internal to external coordinates, may be numerically simulated.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Torque-induced precession (**gyroscopic precession**) is the phenomenon in which the axis of a spinning object (e.g., a gyroscope) describes a cone in space when an external torque is applied to it.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] The phenomenon is commonly seen in a spinning toy top, but all rotating objects can undergo precession.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] If the speed of the rotation and the magnitude of the external torque are constant, the spin axis will move at right angles to the direction that would intuitively result from the external torque.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] In the case of a toy top, its weight is acting downwards from its center of mass and the normal force (reaction) of the ground is pushing up on it at the point of contact with the support.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] These two opposite forces produce a torque which causes the top to precess.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] The device depicted on the right is gimbal-mounted.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] From inside to outside there are three axes of rotation: the hub of the wheel, the gimbal axis, and the vertical pivot.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] To distinguish between the two horizontal axes, rotation around the wheel hub will be called *spinning*, and rotation around the gimbal axis will be called *pitching*.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Rotation around the vertical pivot axis is called *rotation*.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] First, imagine that the entire device is rotating around the (vertical) pivot axis.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Then, spinning of the wheel (around the wheelhub) is added.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Imagine the gimbal axis to be locked, so that the wheel cannot pitch.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] The gimbal axis has sensors, that measure whether there is a torque around the gimbal axis.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] In the picture, a section of the wheel has been named *dm*1.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] At the depicted moment in time, section *dm*1 is at the perimeter of the rotating motion around the (vertical) pivot axis.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Section *dm*2 of the wheel is moving away from the pivot axis, and so a force (again, a Coriolis force) acts in the same direction as in the case of *dm*1.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Note that both arrows point in the same direction.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] The same reasoning applies for the bottom half of the wheel, but there the arrows point in the opposite direction to that of the top arrows.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Combined over the entire wheel, there is a torque around the gimbal axis when some spinning is added to rotation around a vertical axis.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] The torque around the gimbal axis arises without any delay; the response is instantaneous.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] In the discussion above, the setup was kept unchanging by preventing pitching around the gimbal axis.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] In the case of a spinning toy top, when the spinning top starts tilting, gravity exerts a torque.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] However, instead of rolling over, the spinning top just pitches a little.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] This pitching motion reorients the spinning top with respect to the torque that is being exerted.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] The result is that the torque exerted by gravity – via the pitching motion – elicits gyroscopic precession (which in turn yields a counter torque against the gravity torque) rather than causing the spinning top to fall to its side.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Precession or gyroscopic considerations have an effect on bicycle performance at high speed.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Precession is also the mechanism behind gyrocompasses.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Precession is the change of angular velocity and angular momentum produced by a torque.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] The general equation that relates the torque to the rate of change of angular momentum is: ${\boldsymbol {\tau }}={\frac {\mathrm {d} \mathbf {L} }{\mathrm {d} t}}$ where ${\boldsymbol {\tau }}$ and $\mathbf {L}$ are the torque and angular momentum vectors respectively.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Due to the way the torque vectors are defined, it is a vector that is perpendicular to the plane of the forces that create it.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Thus it may be seen that the angular momentum vector will change perpendicular to those forces.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Depending on how the forces are created, they will often rotate with the angular momentum vector, and then circular precession is created.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] where *I*s is the moment of inertia, ***ω***s is the angular velocity of spin about the spin axis, m is the mass, *g* is the acceleration due to gravity, θ is the angle between the spin axis and the axis of precession and *r* is the distance between the center of mass and the pivot.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] The torque vector originates at the center of mass.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Where *I*s is the moment of inertia, *T*s is the period of spin about the spin axis, and **τ** is the torque.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] In general, the problem is more complicated than this, however.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] The special and general theories of relativity give three types of corrections to the Newtonian precession, of a gyroscope near a large mass such as Earth, described above.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] The Schwarzschild geodesics (sometimes Schwarzschild precession) are used in the prediction of the anomalous perihelion precession of the planets, most notably for the accurate prediction of the apsidal precession of Mercury.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] In astronomy, precession refers to any of several gravity-induced, slow and continuous changes in an astronomical body's rotational axis or orbital path.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Precession of the equinoxes, perihelion precession, changes in the tilt of Earth's axis to its orbit, and the eccentricity of its orbit over tens of thousands of years are all important parts of the astronomical theory of ice ages.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Axial precession is the movement of the rotational axis of an astronomical body, whereby the axis slowly traces out a cone.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] In the case of Earth, this type of precession is also known as the *precession of the equinoxes*, *lunisolar precession*, or *precession of the equator*.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Earth goes through one such complete precessional cycle in a period of approximately 26,000 years or 1° every 72 years, during which the positions of stars will slowly change in both equatorial coordinates and ecliptic longitude.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Over this cycle, Earth's north axial pole moves from where it is now, within 1° of Polaris, in a circle around the ecliptic pole, with an angular radius of about 23.5°.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] The ancient Greek astronomer Hipparchus (c.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] 190–120 BC) is generally accepted to be the earliest known astronomer to recognize and assess the precession of the equinoxes at about 1° per century (which is not far from the actual value for antiquity, 1.38°), although there is some minor dispute about whether he was.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] In ancient China, the Jin dynasty scholar-official Yu Xi (fl.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] 307–345 AD) made a similar discovery centuries later, noting that the position of the Sun during the winter solstice had drifted roughly one degree over the course of fifty years relative to the position of the stars.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] The precession of Earth's axis was later explained by Newtonian physics.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Being an oblate spheroid, Earth has a non-spherical shape, bulging outward at the equator.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] The gravitational tidal forces of the Moon and Sun apply torque to the equator, attempting to pull the equatorial bulge into the plane of the ecliptic, but instead causing it to precess.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] The torque exerted by the planets, particularly Jupiter, also plays a role.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Precessional movement of the axis (left), precession of the equinox in relation to the distant stars (middle), and the path of the north celestial pole among the stars due to the precession.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Vega is the bright star near the bottom (right).
[src:imu-sensors/precession] This is called perihelion precession or apsidal precession.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] In the adjunct image, Earth's apsidal precession is illustrated.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] As the Earth travels around the Sun, its elliptical orbit rotates gradually over time.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] The eccentricity of its ellipse and the precession rate of its orbit are exaggerated for visualization.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Most orbits in the Solar System have a much smaller eccentricity and precess at a much slower rate, making them nearly circular and nearly stationary.
[src:imu-sensors/precession] Deviating from Newton's law, Einstein's theory of gravitation predicts an extra term of ⁠*A*/*r*4⁠, which accurately gives the observed excess turning rate of 43 arcseconds per century.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] The data sources for a fusion process are not specified to originate from identical sensors.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] One can distinguish *direct fusion*, *indirect fusion* and fusion of the outputs of the former two.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] Direct fusion is the fusion of sensor data from a set of heterogeneous or homogeneous sensors, soft sensors, and history values of sensor data, while indirect fusion uses information sources like *a priori* knowledge about the environment and human input.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] Sensor fusion is also known as *(multi-sensor) data fusion* and is a subset of *information fusion*.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] Two example sensor fusion calculations are illustrated below.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] Let ${x}_{1}$ and ${x}_{2}$ denote two estimates from two independent sensor measurements, with noise variances $\scriptstyle \sigma _{1}^{2}$ and $\scriptstyle \sigma _{2}^{2}$ , respectively.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] It can be seen that the fused result is simply a linear combination of the two measurements weighted by their respective information.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] It is worth noting that if ${x}$ is a random variable.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] The estimates ${x}_{1}$ and ${x}_{2}$ will be correlated through common process noise, which will cause the estimate ${x}_{3}$ to lose conservativeness.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] Another (equivalent) method to fuse two measurements is to use the optimal Kalman filter.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] Suppose that the data is generated by a first-order system and let ${\textbf {P}}_{k}$ denote the solution of the filter's Riccati equation.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] By inspection, when the first measurement is noise free, the filter ignores the second measurement and vice versa.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] That is, the combined estimate is weighted by the quality of the measurements.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] In sensor fusion, centralized versus decentralized refers to where the fusion of the data occurs.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] In centralized fusion, the clients simply forward all of the data to a central location, and some entity at the central location is responsible for correlating and fusing the data.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] In decentralized, the clients take full responsibility for fusing the data.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] Multiple combinations of centralized and decentralized systems exist.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] Another classification of sensor configuration refers to the coordination of information flow between sensors.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] These mechanisms provide a way to resolve conflicts or disagreements and to allow the development of dynamic sensing strategies.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] Sensors are in redundant (or competitive) configuration if each node delivers independent measures of the same properties.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] This configuration can be used in error correction when comparing information from multiple nodes.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] Redundant strategies are often used with high level fusions in voting procedures.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] Complementary configuration occurs when multiple information sources supply different information about the same features.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] This strategy is used for fusing information at raw data level within decision-making algorithms.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] Complementary features are typically applied in motion recognition tasks with neural network, hidden Markov model, support vector machine, clustering methods and other techniques.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] Cooperative sensor fusion uses the information extracted by multiple independent sensors to provide information that would not be available from single sensors.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] For example, sensors connected to body segments are used for the detection of the angle between them.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] Cooperative sensor strategy gives information impossible to obtain from single nodes.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] Cooperative information fusion can be used in motion recognition, gait analysis, motion analysis,,.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] There are several categories or levels of sensor fusion that are commonly used.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] Sensor fusion level can also be defined basing on the kind of information used to feed the fusion algorithm.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] More precisely, sensor fusion can be performed fusing raw data coming from different sources, extrapolated features or even decision made by single nodes.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] One application of sensor fusion is GPS/INS, where Global Positioning System and inertial navigation system data is fused using various different methods, e.g. the extended Kalman filter.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] This is useful, for example, in determining the attitude of an aircraft using low-cost sensors.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] Another example is using the data fusion approach to determine the traffic state (low traffic, traffic jam, medium flow) using road side collected acoustic, image and sensor data.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] In the field of autonomous driving, sensor fusion is used to combine the redundant information from complementary sensors in order to obtain a more accurate and reliable representation of the environment.
[src:imu-sensors/sensor-fusion] Although technically not a dedicated sensor fusion method, modern convolutional neural network based methods can simultaneously process many channels of sensor data (such as hyperspectral imaging with hundreds of bands ) and fuse relevant information to produce classification results.
